# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: maxwell-equations
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:maxwell-equations/ampère-s-circuital-law] In classical electromagnetism, **Ampère's circuital law**, often simply called **Ampère's law**, and sometimes **Oersted's law**, relates the circulation of a magnetic field around a closed loop to the electric current passing through that loop.
[src:maxwell-equations/ampère-s-circuital-law] The law was inspired by Hans Christian Ørsted's 1820 discovery that an electric current generates a magnetic field.
[src:maxwell-equations/ampère-s-circuital-law] This finding prompted theoretical and experimental work by André-Marie Ampère and others, eventually leading to the formulation of the law in its modern form.
[src:maxwell-equations/ampère-s-circuital-law] James Clerk Maxwell published the law in 1855.
[src:maxwell-equations/ampère-s-circuital-law] In 1865, he generalized the law to account for time-varying electric currents by introducing the displacement current term.
[src:maxwell-equations/ampère-s-circuital-law] The resulting equation, often called the **Ampère–Maxwell law**, is one of Maxwell's equations that form the foundation of classical electromagnetism.
[src:maxwell-equations/ampère-s-circuital-law] Until the early 19th century, electricity and magnetism were thought to be completely separate phenomena.
[src:maxwell-equations/ampère-s-circuital-law] This view changed in 1820 when Danish physicist Hans Christian Ørsted discovered that an electric current produces a magnetic effect.
[src:maxwell-equations/ampère-s-circuital-law] He observed that a compass needle placed near a current-carrying wire deflected so that it aligned perpendicular to the wire.
[src:maxwell-equations/ampère-s-circuital-law] In a series of experiments, Ørsted demonstrated that the current could influence magnetic poles nearby, and that its effect extended outward from the wire.
[src:maxwell-equations/ampère-s-circuital-law] He also observed that this magnetic influence formed a vortex around the wire.
[src:maxwell-equations/ampère-s-circuital-law] Ørsted's discovery sparked a great deal of research into the relation between electricity and magnetism.
[src:maxwell-equations/ampère-s-circuital-law] André-Marie Ampère investigated the magnetic force between two current-carrying wires, discovering Ampère's force law.
[src:maxwell-equations/ampère-s-circuital-law] In the 1850s, Scottish mathematical physicist James Clerk Maxwell generalized these results and others into a single mathematical law.
[src:maxwell-equations/ampère-s-circuital-law] The original form of Maxwell's circuital law, which he discussed in 1854 in correspondence with William Thomson (later ennobled as Lord Kelvin) and published in his 1855 paper "On Faraday's Lines of Force", was based on an analogy to hydrodynamics.
[src:maxwell-equations/ampère-s-circuital-law] The original circuital law relates magnetic fields to electric currents that produce them and can be used to determine either the magnetic field associated with a given current, or the current associated with a given magnetic field.
[src:maxwell-equations/ampère-s-circuital-law] However, it applies only in magnetostatic situations, involving steady, continuous currents flowing in closed circuits.
[src:maxwell-equations/ampère-s-circuital-law] In systems where electric fields vary with time, the original law (as given in this section) must be modified by adding a term known as Maxwell's correction (see below).
[src:maxwell-equations/ampère-s-circuital-law] The integral form of the original circuital law is a line integral of the magnetic field around some closed curve C (arbitrary but must be closed).
[src:maxwell-equations/ampère-s-circuital-law] The curve C in turn bounds both a surface S which the electric current passes through (again arbitrary but not closed—since no three-dimensional volume is enclosed by S), and encloses the current.
[src:maxwell-equations/ampère-s-circuital-law] The mathematical statement of the law is a relation between the circulation of the magnetic field around some path (line integral) due to the current which passes through that enclosed path (surface integral).
[src:maxwell-equations/ampère-s-circuital-law] In terms of total current, (which is the sum of both free current and bound current) the line integral of the magnetic **B**-field (in teslas, T) around closed curve C is proportional to the total current *I*enc passing through a surface S (enclosed by C).
[src:maxwell-equations/ampère-s-circuital-law] In terms of free current, the line integral of the magnetic **H**-field (in amperes per metre, A·m−1) around closed curve C equals the free current *I*f,enc through a surface S.
[src:maxwell-equations/ampère-s-circuital-law] There are a number of ambiguities in the above definitions that require clarification and a choice of convention.
[src:maxwell-equations/ampère-s-circuital-law] Second, there are infinitely many possible surfaces S that have the curve C as their border.
[src:maxwell-equations/ampère-s-circuital-law] (Imagine a soap film on a wire loop, which can be deformed by blowing on the film).
[src:maxwell-equations/ampère-s-circuital-law] Which of those surfaces is to be chosen?
[src:maxwell-equations/ampère-s-circuital-law] If the loop does not lie in a single plane, for example, there is no one obvious choice.
[src:maxwell-equations/ampère-s-circuital-law] The answer is that it does not matter: in the magnetostatic case, the current density is solenoidal (see next section), so the divergence theorem and continuity equation imply that the flux through any surface with boundary C, with the same sign convention, is the same.
[src:maxwell-equations/ampère-s-circuital-law] In practice, one usually chooses the most convenient surface (with the given boundary) to integrate over.
[src:maxwell-equations/ampère-s-circuital-law] The electric current that arises in the simplest textbook situations would be classified as "free current"—for example, the current that passes through a wire or battery.
[src:maxwell-equations/ampère-s-circuital-law] In contrast, "bound current" arises in the context of bulk materials that can be magnetized and/or polarized.
[src:maxwell-equations/ampère-s-circuital-law] When a material is magnetized (for example, by placing it in an external magnetic field), the electrons remain bound to their respective atoms, but behave as if they were orbiting the nucleus in a particular direction, creating a microscopic current.
[src:maxwell-equations/ampère-s-circuital-law] When the currents from all these atoms are put together, they create the same effect as a macroscopic current, circulating perpetually around the magnetized object.
[src:maxwell-equations/ampère-s-circuital-law] This magnetization current **J**M is one contribution to "bound current".
[src:maxwell-equations/ampère-s-circuital-law] The other source of bound current is bound charge.
[src:maxwell-equations/ampère-s-circuital-law] When an electric field is applied, the positive and negative bound charges can separate over atomic distances in polarizable materials, and when the bound charges move, the polarization changes, creating another contribution to the "bound current", the polarization current **J**P.
[src:maxwell-equations/ampère-s-circuital-law] with **J**f the "free" or "conduction" current density.
[src:maxwell-equations/ampère-s-circuital-law] All current is fundamentally the same, microscopically.
[src:maxwell-equations/ampère-s-circuital-law] Nevertheless, there are often practical reasons for wanting to treat bound current differently from free current.
[src:maxwell-equations/ampère-s-circuital-law] For example, the bound current usually originates over atomic dimensions, and one may wish to take advantage of a simpler theory intended for larger dimensions.
[src:maxwell-equations/ampère-s-circuital-law] The result is that the more microscopic Ampère's circuital law, expressed in terms of **B** and the microscopic current (which includes free, magnetization and polarization currents), is sometimes put into the equivalent form below in terms of **H** and the free current only.
[src:maxwell-equations/ampère-s-circuital-law] For a detailed definition of free current and bound current, and the proof that the two formulations are equivalent, see the "proof" section below.
[src:maxwell-equations/ampère-s-circuital-law] There are two important issues regarding the circuital law that require closer scrutiny.
[src:maxwell-equations/ampère-s-circuital-law] First, there is an issue regarding the continuity equation for electrical charge.
[src:maxwell-equations/ampère-s-circuital-law] In vector calculus, the identity for the divergence of a curl states that the divergence of the curl of a vector field must always be zero.
[src:maxwell-equations/ampère-s-circuital-law] Hence $\nabla \cdot (\nabla \times \mathbf {B} )=0\,,$ and so the original Ampère's circuital law implies that $\nabla \cdot \mathbf {J} =0\,,$ i.e. that the current density is solenoidal.
[src:maxwell-equations/ampère-s-circuital-law] But in general, reality follows the continuity equation for electric charge: $\nabla \cdot \mathbf {J} =-{\frac {\partial \rho }{\partial t}}\,,$ which is nonzero for a time-varying charge density.
[src:maxwell-equations/ampère-s-circuital-law] An example occurs in a capacitor circuit where time-varying charge densities exist on the plates.
[src:maxwell-equations/ampère-s-circuital-law] Second, there is an issue regarding the propagation of electromagnetic waves.
[src:maxwell-equations/ampère-s-circuital-law] To 'resolve' these situations (w/ eqn. above), the contribution of displacement current must be added to the current term in the circuital law.
[src:maxwell-equations/ampère-s-circuital-law] James Clerk Maxwell conceived of displacement current as a polarization current in the dielectric vortex sea, which he used to model the magnetic field hydrodynamically and mechanically.
[src:maxwell-equations/ampère-s-circuital-law] He added this displacement current to Ampère's circuital law at equation 112 in his 1861 paper "On Physical Lines of Force".
[src:maxwell-equations/ampère-s-circuital-law] In free space, the displacement current is related to the time rate of change of electric field.
[src:maxwell-equations/ampère-s-circuital-law] In a dielectric the above contribution to displacement current is present too, but a major contribution to the displacement current is related to the polarization of the individual molecules of the dielectric material.
[src:maxwell-equations/ampère-s-circuital-law] Even though charges cannot flow freely in a dielectric, the charges in molecules can move a little under the influence of an electric field.
[src:maxwell-equations/ampère-s-circuital-law] The positive and negative charges in molecules separate under the applied field, causing an increase in the state of polarization, expressed as the polarization density **P**.
[src:maxwell-equations/ampère-s-circuital-law] A changing state of polarization is equivalent to a current.
[src:maxwell-equations/ampère-s-circuital-law] The first term on the right hand side is present everywhere, even in a vacuum.
[src:maxwell-equations/ampère-s-circuital-law] It doesn't involve any actual movement of charge, but it nevertheless has an associated magnetic field, as if it were an actual current.
[src:maxwell-equations/ampère-s-circuital-law] Some authors apply the name *displacement current* to only this contribution.
[src:maxwell-equations/ampère-s-circuital-law] The second term on the right hand side is the displacement current as originally conceived by Maxwell, associated with the polarization of the individual molecules of the dielectric material.
[src:maxwell-equations/ampère-s-circuital-law] Maxwell's original explanation for displacement current focused upon the situation that occurs in dielectric media.
[src:maxwell-equations/ampère-s-circuital-law] In the modern post-aether era, the concept has been extended to apply to situations with no material media present, for example, to the vacuum between the plates of a charging vacuum capacitor.
[src:maxwell-equations/ampère-s-circuital-law] For greater discussion see Displacement current.
[src:maxwell-equations/ampère-s-circuital-law] Next, the circuital equation is extended by including the polarization current, thereby remedying the limited applicability of the original circuital law.
[src:maxwell-equations/ampère-s-circuital-law] In both forms **J** includes magnetization current density as well as conduction and polarization current densities.
[src:maxwell-equations/ampère-s-circuital-law] Because ∇ ⋅ **D** = *ρ*, the charge continuity issue with Ampère's original formulation is no longer a problem.
[src:maxwell-equations/ampère-s-circuital-law] Because of the term in *ε*0⁠∂**E**/∂*t*⁠, wave propagation in free space now is possible.
[src:maxwell-equations/ampère-s-circuital-law] With the addition of the displacement current, Maxwell was able to hypothesize (correctly) that light was a form of electromagnetic wave.
[src:maxwell-equations/ampère-s-circuital-law] See electromagnetic wave equation for a discussion of this important discovery.
[src:maxwell-equations/displacement-current] In electromagnetism, **displacement current density** is the rate of change of the electric displacement field **D**, appearing as ∂**D**/∂*t* in Maxwell's equations.
[src:maxwell-equations/displacement-current] Displacement current density has the same units as electric current density, and it is a source of the magnetic field just as actual current is.
[src:maxwell-equations/displacement-current] However it is not an electric current of moving charges, but a time-varying electric field.
[src:maxwell-equations/displacement-current] In physical materials (as opposed to vacuum), there is also a contribution from the slight motion of charges bound in atoms, called dielectric polarization.
[src:maxwell-equations/displacement-current] The idea was conceived by James Clerk Maxwell in his 1861 paper "On Physical Lines of Force" (Part III) in connection with the displacement of electric particles in a dielectric medium.
[src:maxwell-equations/displacement-current] Maxwell added displacement current to the electric current term in Ampère's circuital law.
[src:maxwell-equations/displacement-current] In his 1865 paper A Dynamical Theory of the Electromagnetic Field Maxwell used this amended version of Ampère's circuital law to derive the electromagnetic wave equation.
[src:maxwell-equations/displacement-current] This derivation is now generally accepted as a historical landmark in physics by virtue of uniting electricity, magnetism and optics into one single unified theory.
[src:maxwell-equations/displacement-current] The displacement current term is now seen as a crucial addition that completed Maxwell's equations and is necessary to explain many phenomena, most particularly the existence of electromagnetic waves.
[src:maxwell-equations/displacement-current] The first term on the right hand side is present in material media and in free space.
[src:maxwell-equations/displacement-current] It doesn't necessarily come from any actual movement of charge, but it does have an associated magnetic field, just as a current does due to charge motion.
[src:maxwell-equations/displacement-current] Some authors apply the name *displacement current* to the first term by itself.
[src:maxwell-equations/displacement-current] The second term on the right hand side, called polarization current density, comes from the change in polarization of the individual molecules of the dielectric material.
[src:maxwell-equations/displacement-current] Polarization results when, under the influence of an applied electric field, the charges in molecules have moved from a position of exact cancellation.
[src:maxwell-equations/displacement-current] The positive and negative charges in molecules separate, causing an increase in the state of polarization **P**.
[src:maxwell-equations/displacement-current] A changing state of polarization corresponds to charge movement and so is equivalent to a current, hence the term "polarization current".
[src:maxwell-equations/displacement-current] This polarization is the displacement current as it was originally conceived by Maxwell.
[src:maxwell-equations/displacement-current] Maxwell made no special treatment of the vacuum, treating it as a material medium.
[src:maxwell-equations/displacement-current] For Maxwell, the effect of **P** was simply to change the relative permittivity *ε*r in the relation **D** = *ε*0*ε*r **E**.
[src:maxwell-equations/displacement-current] The modern justification of displacement current is explained below.
[src:maxwell-equations/displacement-current] In the equation above, the use of ε accounts for the polarization (if any) of the dielectric material.
[src:maxwell-equations/displacement-current] The forms in terms of scalar ε are correct only for linear isotropic materials.
[src:maxwell-equations/displacement-current] For linear non-isotropic materials, ε becomes a matrix; even more generally, ε may be replaced by a tensor, which may depend upon the electric field itself, or may exhibit frequency dependence (hence dispersion).
[src:maxwell-equations/displacement-current] where *χ*e is known as the *susceptibility* of the dielectric to electric fields.
[src:maxwell-equations/displacement-current] Some implications of the displacement current follow, which agree with experimental observation, and with the requirements of logical consistency for the theory of electromagnetism.
[src:maxwell-equations/displacement-current] An example illustrating the need for the displacement current arises in connection with capacitors with no medium between the plates.
[src:maxwell-equations/displacement-current] Consider the charging capacitor in the figure.
[src:maxwell-equations/displacement-current] The capacitor is in a circuit that causes equal and opposite charges to appear on the left plate and the right plate, charging the capacitor and increasing the electric field between its plates.
[src:maxwell-equations/displacement-current] No actual charge is transported through the vacuum between its plates.
[src:maxwell-equations/displacement-current] Nonetheless, a magnetic field exists between the plates as though a current were present there as well.
[src:maxwell-equations/displacement-current] which extends the notion of current beyond a mere transport of charge.
[src:maxwell-equations/displacement-current] Next, this displacement current is related to the charging of the capacitor.
[src:maxwell-equations/displacement-current] Consider the current in the imaginary cylindrical surface shown surrounding the left plate.
[src:maxwell-equations/displacement-current] A current, say I, passes outward through the left surface L of the cylinder, but no conduction current (no transport of real charges) crosses the right surface R.
[src:maxwell-equations/displacement-current] Notice that the electric field **E** between the plates increases as the capacitor charges.
[src:maxwell-equations/displacement-current] where S refers to the imaginary cylindrical surface.
[src:maxwell-equations/displacement-current] where the first term has a negative sign because charge leaves surface L (the charge is decreasing), the last term has a positive sign because unit vector of surface R is from left to right while the direction of electric field is from right to left, S is the area of the surface R.
[src:maxwell-equations/displacement-current] The electric field at surface L is zero because surface L is in the outside of the capacitor.
[src:maxwell-equations/displacement-current] where **I** is the current leaving the cylindrical surface (which must equal **I**D) and **J**D is the flow of charge per unit area into the cylindrical surface through the face R.
[src:maxwell-equations/displacement-current] As depicted in the figure to the right, the current crossing surface *S*1 is entirely conduction current.
[src:maxwell-equations/displacement-current] However, the current crossing surface *S*2 is entirely displacement current.
[src:maxwell-equations/displacement-current] Any surface *S*1 that intersects the wire has current I passing through it so Ampère's law gives the correct magnetic field.
[src:maxwell-equations/displacement-current] However a second surface *S*2 bounded by the same edge ⁠ $\partial S$ ⁠ could be drawn passing between the capacitor plates, therefore having no current passing through it.
[src:maxwell-equations/displacement-current] Without the displacement current term Ampere's law would give zero magnetic field for this surface.
[src:maxwell-equations/displacement-current] Therefore, without the displacement current term Ampere's law gives inconsistent results, the magnetic field would depend on the surface chosen for integration.
[src:maxwell-equations/displacement-current] Thus the displacement current term ⁠ $\varepsilon _{0}\partial \mathbf {E} /\partial t$ ⁠ is necessary as a second source term which gives the correct magnetic field when the surface of integration passes between the capacitor plates.
[src:maxwell-equations/displacement-current] Because the current is increasing the charge on the capacitor's plates, the electric field between the plates is increasing, and the rate of change of electric field gives the correct value for the field **B** found above.
[src:maxwell-equations/displacement-current] In a more mathematical vein, the same results can be obtained from the underlying differential equations.
[src:maxwell-equations/displacement-current] Consider for simplicity a non-magnetic medium where the relative magnetic permeability is unity, and the complication of magnetization current (bound current) is absent, so that $\mathbf {M} =0$ and $\mathbf {J} =\mathbf {J} _{\mathrm {f} }$ .
[src:maxwell-equations/displacement-current] The current leaving a volume must equal the rate of decrease of charge in a volume.
[src:maxwell-equations/displacement-current] where the left side is the divergence of the free current density and the right side is the rate of decrease of the free charge density.
[src:maxwell-equations/displacement-current] which implies that the divergence of the current term vanishes, contradicting the continuity equation.
[src:maxwell-equations/displacement-current] The added displacement current also leads to wave propagation by taking the curl of the equation for magnetic field.
[src:maxwell-equations/displacement-current] and the fact that the divergence of the magnetic field is zero.
[src:maxwell-equations/displacement-current] where φ is the electric potential (which can be chosen to satisfy Poisson's equation) and **A** is a vector potential (i.e. magnetic vector potential, not to be confused with surface area, as **A** is denoted elsewhere).
[src:maxwell-equations/displacement-current] The ∇*φ* component on the right hand side is the Gauss's law component, and this is the component that is relevant to the conservation of charge argument above.
[src:maxwell-equations/displacement-current] The second term on the right-hand side is the one relevant to the electromagnetic wave equation, because it is the term that contributes to the curl of **E**.
[src:maxwell-equations/displacement-current] Because of the vector identity that says the curl of a gradient is zero, ∇*φ* does not contribute to ∇×**E**.
[src:maxwell-equations/displacement-current] Maxwell's displacement current was postulated in part III of his 1861 paper 'On Physical Lines of Force'.
[src:maxwell-equations/displacement-current] Few topics in modern physics have caused as much confusion and misunderstanding as that of displacement current.
[src:maxwell-equations/displacement-current] This is in part due to the fact that Maxwell used a sea of molecular vortices in his derivation, while modern textbooks operate on the basis that displacement current can exist in free space.
[src:maxwell-equations/displacement-current] Maxwell's derivation is unrelated to the modern day derivation for displacement current in the vacuum, which is based on consistency between Ampère's circuital law for the magnetic field and the continuity equation for electric charge.
[src:maxwell-equations/displacement-current] Maxwell's purpose is stated by him at (Part I, p.
[src:maxwell-equations/displacement-current] Clearly Maxwell was driving at magnetization even though the same introduction clearly talks about dielectric polarization.
[src:maxwell-equations/displacement-current] Maxwell compared the speed of electricity measured by Wilhelm Eduard Weber and Rudolf Kohlrausch (193,088 miles/second) and the speed of light determined by the Fizeau experiment (195,647 miles/second).
[src:maxwell-equations/displacement-current] — *On Physical Lines of Force*, Part III, *The theory of molecular vortices applied to statical electricity*, pp.
[src:maxwell-equations/displacement-current] Maxwell's emphasis on polarization diverted attention towards the electric capacitor circuit, and led to the common belief that Maxwell conceived of displacement current so as to maintain conservation of charge in an electric capacitor circuit.
[src:maxwell-equations/displacement-current] There are a variety of debatable notions about Maxwell's thinking, ranging from his supposed desire to perfect the symmetry of the field equations to the desire to achieve compatibility with the continuity equation.
[src:maxwell-equations/electric-potential] By dividing out the charge on the particle a quotient is obtained that is a property of the electric field itself.
[src:maxwell-equations/electric-potential] In short, an electric potential is the electric potential energy per unit charge.
[src:maxwell-equations/electric-potential] This value can be calculated in either a static (time-invariant) or a dynamic (time-varying) electric field at a specific time with the unit joules per coulomb (J⋅C−1) or volt (V).
[src:maxwell-equations/electric-potential] The electric potential at infinity is assumed to be zero.
[src:maxwell-equations/electric-potential] In electrodynamics, when time-varying fields are present, the electric field cannot be expressed only as a scalar potential.
[src:maxwell-equations/electric-potential] Instead, the electric field can be expressed as both the scalar electric potential and the magnetic vector potential.
[src:maxwell-equations/electric-potential] The electric potential and the magnetic vector potential together form a four-vector, so that the two kinds of potential are mixed under Lorentz transformations.
[src:maxwell-equations/electric-potential] Practically, the electric potential is a continuous function in all space, because a spatial derivative of a discontinuous electric potential yields an electric field of impossibly infinite magnitude.
[src:maxwell-equations/electric-potential] Notably, the electric potential due to an idealized point charge (proportional to 1 ⁄ *r*, with *r* the distance from the point charge) is continuous in all space except at the location of the point charge.
[src:maxwell-equations/electric-potential] Though electric field is not continuous across an idealized surface charge, it is not infinite at any point.
[src:maxwell-equations/electric-potential] Therefore, the electric potential is continuous across an idealized surface charge.
[src:maxwell-equations/electric-potential] Additionally, an idealized line of charge has electric potential (proportional to ln(*r*), with *r* the radial distance from the line of charge) is continuous everywhere except on the line of charge.
[src:maxwell-equations/electric-potential] Classical mechanics explores concepts such as force, energy, and potential.
[src:maxwell-equations/electric-potential] Force and potential energy are directly related.
[src:maxwell-equations/electric-potential] A net force acting on any object will cause it to accelerate.
[src:maxwell-equations/electric-potential] As an object moves in the direction of a force acting on it, its potential energy decreases.
[src:maxwell-equations/electric-potential] For example, the gravitational potential energy of a cannonball at the top of a hill is greater than at the base of the hill.
[src:maxwell-equations/electric-potential] As it rolls downhill, its potential energy decreases and is being translated to motion – kinetic energy.
[src:maxwell-equations/electric-potential] It is possible to define the potential of certain force fields so that the potential energy of an object in that field depends only on the position of the object with respect to the field.
[src:maxwell-equations/electric-potential] Two such force fields are a gravitational field and an electric field (in the absence of time-varying magnetic fields).
[src:maxwell-equations/electric-potential] Such fields affect objects because of the intrinsic properties (e.g., mass or charge) and positions of the objects.
[src:maxwell-equations/electric-potential] An object may possess a property known as electric charge.
[src:maxwell-equations/electric-potential] Since an electric field exerts force on a charged object, if the object has a positive charge, the force will be in the direction of the electric field vector at the location of the charge; if the charge is negative, the force will be in the opposite direction.
[src:maxwell-equations/electric-potential] Electric potential around separate positive and negative point charges shown as color range from magenta (+), through yellow (0), to cyan (−).
[src:maxwell-equations/electric-potential] Circular contours are equipotential lines.
[src:maxwell-equations/electric-potential] Electric field lines leave the positive charge and enter the negative charge.
[src:maxwell-equations/electric-potential] Electric potential in the vicinity of two opposite point charges.
[src:maxwell-equations/electric-potential] where C is an arbitrary path from some fixed reference point to **r**; it is uniquely determined up to a constant that is added or subtracted from the integral.
[src:maxwell-equations/electric-potential] In electrostatics, the Maxwell-Faraday equation reveals that the curl ${\textstyle \nabla \times \mathbf {E} }$ is zero, making the electric field conservative.
[src:maxwell-equations/electric-potential] Thus, the line integral above does not depend on the specific path C chosen but only on its endpoints, making ${\textstyle V_{\mathbf {E} }}$ well-defined everywhere.
[src:maxwell-equations/electric-potential] This states that the electric field points "downhill" towards lower voltages.
[src:maxwell-equations/electric-potential] where ρ is the total charge density and ${\textstyle \mathbf {\nabla } \cdot }$ denotes the divergence.
[src:maxwell-equations/electric-potential] The concept of electric potential is closely linked with potential energy.
[src:maxwell-equations/electric-potential] The potential energy and hence, also the electric potential, is only defined up to an additive constant: one must arbitrarily choose a position where the potential energy and the electric potential are zero.
[src:maxwell-equations/electric-potential] These equations cannot be used if ${\textstyle \nabla \times \mathbf {E} \neq \mathbf {0} }$ , i.e., in the case of a *non-conservative electric field* (caused by a changing magnetic field; see Maxwell's equations).
[src:maxwell-equations/electric-potential] The generalization of electric potential to this case is described in the section § Generalization to electrodynamics.
[src:maxwell-equations/electric-potential] The electric potential arising from a point charge, *Q*, at a distance, *r*, from the location of *Q* is observed to be $V_{\mathbf {E} }={\frac {1}{4\pi \varepsilon _{0}}}{\frac {Q}{r}},$ where *ε*0 is the permittivity of vacuum, *V***E** is known as the **Coulomb potential**.
[src:maxwell-equations/electric-potential] Note that, in contrast to the magnitude of an electric field due to a point charge, the electric potential scales respective to the reciprocal of the radius, rather than the radius squared.
[src:maxwell-equations/electric-potential] The electric potential at any location, **r**, in a system of point charges is equal to the sum of the individual electric potentials due to every point charge in the system.
[src:maxwell-equations/electric-potential] This fact simplifies calculations significantly, because addition of potential (scalar) fields is much easier than addition of the electric (vector) fields.
[src:maxwell-equations/electric-potential] The equations given above for the electric potential (and all the equations used here) are in the forms required by SI units.
[src:maxwell-equations/electric-potential] In some other (less common) systems of units, such as CGS-Gaussian, many of these equations would be altered.
[src:maxwell-equations/electric-potential] Instead, one can still define a scalar potential by also including the magnetic vector potential **A**.
[src:maxwell-equations/electric-potential] By the fundamental theorem of vector calculus, such an **A** can always be found, since the divergence of the magnetic field is always zero due to the absence of magnetic monopoles.
[src:maxwell-equations/electric-potential] Now, the quantity $\mathbf {F} =\mathbf {E} +{\frac {\partial \mathbf {A} }{\partial t}}$ *is* a conservative field, since the curl of $\mathbf {E}$ is canceled by the curl of ${\frac {\partial \mathbf {A} }{\partial t}}$ according to the Maxwell–Faraday equation.
[src:maxwell-equations/electric-potential] where *V* is the scalar potential defined by the conservative field **F**.
[src:maxwell-equations/electric-potential] The electrostatic potential is simply the special case of this definition where **A** is time-invariant.
[src:maxwell-equations/electric-potential] On the other hand, for time-varying fields, $-\int _{a}^{b}\mathbf {E} \cdot \mathrm {d} {\boldsymbol {\ell }}\neq V_{(b)}-V_{(a)}$ unlike electrostatics.
[src:maxwell-equations/electric-potential] The electrostatic potential could have any constant added to it without affecting the electric field.
[src:maxwell-equations/electric-potential] In electrodynamics, the electric potential has infinitely many degrees of freedom.
[src:maxwell-equations/electric-potential] Given different choices of gauge, the electric potential could have quite different properties.
[src:maxwell-equations/electric-potential] The SI derived unit of electric potential is the volt (in honor of Alessandro Volta), denoted as V, which is why the electric potential difference between two points in space is known as a voltage.
[src:maxwell-equations/electric-potential] Variants of the centimetre–gram–second system of units included a number of different units for electric potential, including the abvolt and the statvolt.
[src:maxwell-equations/electric-potential] Inside metals (and other solids and liquids), the energy of an electron is affected not only by the electric potential, but also by the specific atomic environment that it is in.
[src:maxwell-equations/electric-potential] When a voltmeter is connected between two different types of metal, it measures the **potential difference** corrected for the different atomic environments.
[src:maxwell-equations/electric-potential] The quantity measured by a voltmeter is called electrochemical potential or fermi level, while the pure unadjusted electric potential, *V*, is sometimes called the Galvani potential, ϕ.
[src:maxwell-equations/electric-potential] The terms "voltage" and "electric potential" are a bit ambiguous but one may refer to *either* of these in different contexts.
[src:maxwell-equations/electromagnetic-wave-equation] The **electromagnetic wave equation** is a second-order partial differential equation that describes the propagation of electromagnetic waves through a medium or in a vacuum.
[src:maxwell-equations/electromagnetic-wave-equation] It is a three-dimensional form of the wave equation.
[src:maxwell-equations/electromagnetic-wave-equation] is the speed of light (i.e. phase velocity) in a medium with permeability μ, and permittivity ε, and ∇2 is the Laplace operator.
[src:maxwell-equations/electromagnetic-wave-equation] In a vacuum, *v*ph = *c*0 = 299792458 m/s, a fundamental physical constant.
[src:maxwell-equations/electromagnetic-wave-equation] The electromagnetic wave equation derives from Maxwell's equations.
[src:maxwell-equations/electromagnetic-wave-equation] In most older literature, **B** is called the *magnetic flux density* or *magnetic induction*.
[src:maxwell-equations/electromagnetic-wave-equation] In his 1865 paper titled A Dynamical Theory of the Electromagnetic Field, James Clerk Maxwell utilized the correction to Ampère's circuital law that he had made in part III of his 1861 paper On Physical Lines of Force.
[src:maxwell-equations/electromagnetic-wave-equation] In *Part VI* of his 1864 paper titled *Electromagnetic Theory of Light*, Maxwell combined displacement current with some of the other equations of electromagnetism and he obtained a wave equation with a speed equal to the speed of light.
[src:maxwell-equations/electromagnetic-wave-equation] Maxwell's derivation of the electromagnetic wave equation has been replaced in modern physics education by a much less cumbersome method involving combining the corrected version of Ampère's circuital law with Faraday's law of induction.
[src:maxwell-equations/electromagnetic-wave-equation] To obtain the electromagnetic wave equation in a vacuum using the modern method, we begin with the modern '**Heaviside' form of Maxwell's equations**.
[src:maxwell-equations/electromagnetic-wave-equation] These are the general Maxwell's equations specialized to the case with charge and current both set to zero.
[src:maxwell-equations/electromagnetic-wave-equation] where **V** is any vector function of space.
[src:maxwell-equations/electromagnetic-wave-equation] where ∇**V** is a dyadic which when operated on by the divergence operator ∇ ⋅ yields a vector.
[src:maxwell-equations/electromagnetic-wave-equation] The electromagnetic wave equation is modified in two ways, the derivative is replaced with the covariant derivative and a new term that depends on the curvature appears.
[src:maxwell-equations/electromagnetic-wave-equation] where ${R^{\alpha }}_{\beta }$ is the Ricci curvature tensor and the semicolon indicates covariant differentiation.
[src:maxwell-equations/electromagnetic-wave-equation] Localized time-varying charge and current densities can act as sources of electromagnetic waves in a vacuum.
[src:maxwell-equations/electromagnetic-wave-equation] Maxwell's equations can be written in the form of a wave equation with sources.
[src:maxwell-equations/electromagnetic-wave-equation] The addition of sources to the wave equations makes the partial differential equations inhomogeneous.
[src:maxwell-equations/electromagnetic-wave-equation] for virtually *any* well-behaved function g of dimensionless argument φ, where ω is the angular frequency (in radians per second), and **k** = (*kx*, *ky*, *kz*) is the wave vector (in radians per meter).
[src:maxwell-equations/electromagnetic-wave-equation] Although the function g can be and often is a monochromatic sine wave, it does not have to be sinusoidal, or even periodic.
[src:maxwell-equations/electromagnetic-wave-equation] In practice, g cannot have infinite periodicity because any real electromagnetic wave must always have a finite extent in time and space.
[src:maxwell-equations/electromagnetic-wave-equation] As a result, and based on the theory of Fourier decomposition, a real wave must consist of the superposition of an infinite set of sinusoidal frequencies.
[src:maxwell-equations/electromagnetic-wave-equation] where k is the wavenumber and λ is the wavelength.
[src:maxwell-equations/electromagnetic-wave-equation] The variable c can only be used in this equation when the electromagnetic wave is in a vacuum.
[src:maxwell-equations/electromagnetic-wave-equation] where **r** = (*x*, *y*, *z*) is the position vector (in meters).
[src:maxwell-equations/electromagnetic-wave-equation] These solutions represent planar waves traveling in the direction of the normal vector **n**.
[src:maxwell-equations/electromagnetic-wave-equation] Because the divergence of the electric and magnetic fields are zero, there are no fields in the direction of propagation.
[src:maxwell-equations/electromagnetic-wave-equation] This solution is the linearly polarized solution of the wave equations.
[src:maxwell-equations/electromagnetic-wave-equation] There are also circularly polarized solutions in which the fields rotate about the normal vector.
[src:maxwell-equations/electromagnetic-wave-equation] Because of the linearity of Maxwell's equations in a vacuum, solutions can be decomposed into a superposition of sinusoids.
[src:maxwell-equations/electromagnetic-wave-equation] This is the basis for the Fourier transform method for the solution of differential equations.
[src:maxwell-equations/electromagnetic-wave-equation] The electromagnetic spectrum is a plot of the field magnitudes (or energies) as a function of wavelength.
[src:maxwell-equations/electromagnetic-wave-equation] A generic electromagnetic field with frequency ω can be written as a sum of solutions to these two equations.
[src:maxwell-equations/electromagnetic-wave-equation] The three-dimensional solutions of the Helmholtz Equation can be expressed as expansions in spherical harmonics with coefficients proportional to the spherical Bessel functions.
[src:maxwell-equations/electromagnetic-wave-equation] However, applying this expansion to each vector component of **E** or **B** will give solutions that are not generically divergence-free (∇ ⋅ **E** = ∇ ⋅ **B** = 0), and therefore require additional restrictions on the coefficients.
[src:maxwell-equations/electromagnetic-wave-equation] The multipole expansion circumvents this difficulty by expanding not **E** or **B**, but **r** ⋅ **E** or **r** ⋅ **B** into spherical harmonics.
[src:maxwell-equations/electromagnetic-wave-equation] These expansions still solve the original Helmholtz equations for **E** and **B** because for a divergence-free field **F**, ∇2 (**r** ⋅ **F**) = **r** ⋅ (∇2 **F**).
[src:maxwell-equations/electromagnetic-wave-equation] The multipole expansion of the electromagnetic field finds application in a number of problems involving spherical symmetry, for example antennae radiation patterns, or nuclear gamma decay.
[src:maxwell-equations/electromagnetic-wave-equation] In these applications, one is often interested in the power radiated in the far-field.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] Motional emf, induced by moving a conductor through a magnetic field.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] Transformer emf, induced by a changing magnetic field.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] In electromagnetism, **Faraday's law of induction** describes how a changing magnetic field can induce an electric current in a circuit.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] This phenomenon, known as electromagnetic induction, is the fundamental operating principle of transformers, inductors, and many types of electric motors, generators and solenoids.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] In the literature, however, *Faraday's law* is used to refer to two closely related but technically distinct statements, either of which can be used to explain the phenomenon of induced current described above.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] One is the **Maxwell–Faraday equation**, one of Maxwell's equations, which states that a time-varying magnetic field is always accompanied by a circulating electric field.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] This law applies to the fields themselves and does not require the presence of a physical circuit.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] The other is **Faraday's flux rule**, or the **Faraday–Lenz law**, which relates the electromotive force (emf) around a closed conducting loop to the time rate of change of magnetic flux through the loop.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] This rule can be derived from the first in specific context of a closed circuit.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] The flux rule accounts for two mechanisms by which an emf can be generated.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] In *transformer emf*, a time-varying magnetic field induces an electric field as described by the Maxwell–Faraday equation, and the electric field drives a current around the loop.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] In *motional emf*, the circuit moves through a magnetic field, and the emf arises from the magnetic component of the Lorentz force acting on the charges in the conductor.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] Historically, the differing explanations for motional emf and transformer emf posed a conceptual problem, since the observed current depends only on relative motion, but the physical explanations were different in the two cases.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] In special relativity, this distinction is understood as frame-dependent: what appears as a magnetic force in one frame may appear as an induced electric field in another.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] In 1820, Hans Christian Ørsted demonstrated that an electric current produces a magnetic field, showing that a compass needle could be deflected by a nearby current-carrying wire.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] This discovery prompted scientists to ask whether the reverse was also true—whether a magnetic field could generate an electric current.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] Initial experiments revealed that a static magnetic field had no effect on a nearby circuit: simply placing a magnet near a wire loop produced no current.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] The breakthrough came in 1831, when Michael Faraday demonstrated that a changing magnetic field could indeed induce an electric current in a circuit.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] Independently, Joseph Henry made similar observations in 1832, though Faraday was the first to publish his findings.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] Faraday's notebook on August 29, 1831 describes an experimental demonstration of induction.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] He wrapped two coils of wire around opposite sides of an iron ring, forming a primitive toroidal transformer.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] When he connected one coil to a battery, he observed a brief deflection in a galvanometer attached to the second coil.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] He concluded that a changing current in the first coil created a changing magnetic field in the ring, which in turn induced a current in the second coil.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] He described this as a "wave of electricity" propagated through the iron.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] Over the following months, Faraday discovered other manifestations of electromagnetic induction.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] He observed transient currents when a bar magnet was rapidly moved into or out of a coil of wire.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] He also built a device, now known as Faraday's disk or homopolar generator, that produced a steady (DC) current by rotating a copper disk in the presence of a stationary magnet, using a sliding electrical contact.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] Faraday explained these phenomena using the concept of lines of force.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] However, his theoretical ideas were met with skepticism, as they were not formulated mathematically.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] Lenz's law, formulated by Emil Lenz in 1834, describes "flux through the circuit", and gives the direction of the induced emf and current resulting from electromagnetic induction (elaborated upon in the examples below).
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] The laws of induction of electric currents in mathematical form were established by Franz Ernst Neumann in 1845.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] Wilhelm Eduard Weber also provided a formulation in terms of Weber electrodynamics.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] Starting in 1851, Riccardo Felici carried out several experiments on induction based on Neumann.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] Felici came up with Felici's law, a version of the law of induction.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] James Clerk Maxwell later gave Faraday's insights mathematical expression, incorporating them into his broader electromagnetic theory in the early 1860s.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] Maxwell cited the works of Faraday, Neumann, Weber and Felici.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] In Maxwell's papers, the time-varying aspect of electromagnetic induction is expressed as a differential equation which Oliver Heaviside referred to as Faraday's law even though it is different from the original version of Faraday's law, and does not describe motional emf.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] Heaviside's version from 1890s is the form recognized today in the group of equations known as Maxwell's equations.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] According to Albert Einstein, much of the groundwork and discovery of his special relativity theory was presented by this law of induction by Faraday in 1834.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] Faraday's law of induction, also known as the *flux rule*, *flux law*, and *Faraday–Lenz law*, states that the electromotive force (emf) around a closed circuit is equal to the negative rate of change of the magnetic flux through the circuit.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] This rule holds for any circuit made of thin wire and accounts for changes in flux due to variations in the magnetic field, movement of the circuit, or deformation of its shape.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] The direction of the induced emf is given by Lenz's law, which states that the induced current will flow in such a way that its magnetic field opposes the change in the original magnetic flux.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] Mathematically, in SI units, the law is expressed as ${\mathcal {E}}=-{\frac {\mathrm {d} \Phi _{B}}{\mathrm {d} t}},$ where ${\mathcal {E}}$ is the electromotive force (emf) and Φ*B* is the magnetic flux through the circuit.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] The magnetic flux is defined as the surface integral of the magnetic field **B** over a time-dependent surface Σ(*t*), whose boundary is the wire loop: $\Phi _{B}=\iint _{\Sigma (t)}\mathbf {B} (t)\cdot \mathrm {d} \mathbf {A} \,,$ where d**A** is an infinitesimal area vector normal to the surface.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] The dot product **B** · d**A** represents the flux through the differential area element.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] In more visual terms, the magnetic flux is proportional to the number of magnetic field lines passing through the loop.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] When the flux changes, an emf is induced around the loop.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] This emf corresponds to the energy per unit charge required to move it once around the loop.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] In a simple circuit with resistance R , an emf ${\mathcal {E}}$ gives rise to a current I according to the Ohm's law ${\mathcal {E}}=IR$ .
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] Equivalently, if the loop is broken to form an open circuit and a voltmeter is connected across the terminals, the emf is equal to the voltage measured across the open ends.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] For a tightly wound coil of wire, composed of N identical turns, the same magnetic field lines cross the surface N times.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] In this case, Faraday's law of induction states that ${\mathcal {E}}=-N{\frac {\mathrm {d} \Phi _{B}}{\mathrm {d} t}}$ where N is the number of turns of wire and Φ*B* is the magnetic flux through a single loop.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] The product *N*Φ*B* is known as linked flux.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] The flux can change either because the loop moves or deforms over time, or because the field itself varies in time.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] The basic mechanism behind motional emf is illustrated by a conducting rod moving through a magnetic field that is perpendicular to both the rod and its direction of motion.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] Due to movement in magnetic field, the mobile electrons of the conductor experience the magnetic component (*q***v** × **B**) of the Lorentz force that drives them along the length of the rod.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] This leads to a separation of charge between the two ends of the rod.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] In the steady state, the electric field from the accumulated charge balances the magnetic force.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] If the rod is part of a closed conducting loop moving through a nonuniform magnetic field, the same effect can drive a current around the circuit.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] For instance, suppose the magnetic field is confined to a limited region of space, and the loop initially lies outside this region.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] As it moves into the field, the area of the loop that encloses magnetic flux increases, and an emf is induced.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] From the Lorentz force perspective, this is because the field exerts a magnetic force on charge carriers in the parts of the loop entering the region.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] Once the entire loop lies in a uniform magnetic field and continues at constant speed, the total enclosed flux remains constant, and the emf vanishes.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] In this situation, magnetic forces on opposite sides of the loop cancel out.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] A complementary case is transformer emf, which occurs when the conducting loop remains stationary but the magnetic flux through it changes due to a time-varying magnetic field.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] This can happen in two ways: either the source of the magnetic field moves, altering the field distribution through the fixed loop, or the strength of the magnetic field changes over time at a fixed location, as in the case of a powered electromagnet.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] In either situation, no magnetic force acts on the charges, and the emf is entirely due to the electric component (*q***E**) of the Lorentz force.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] According to the Maxwell–Faraday equation, a time-varying magnetic field produces a circulating electric field, which drives current in the loop.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] This phenomenon underlies the operation of electrical machines such as synchronous generators.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] The electric field induced in this way is non-conservative, meaning its line integral around a closed loop is not zero.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] It is possible to find out the direction of the electromotive force (emf) directly from Faraday's law, without invoking Lenz's law.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] The Maxwell–Faraday equation is one of the four Maxwell's equations, and therefore plays a fundamental role in the theory of classical electromagnetism.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] It states that a time-varying magnetic field always accompanies a spatially varying, non-conservative electric field.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] where ∇ × is the curl operator, **E**(**r**, *t*) is the electric field and **B**(**r**, *t*) is the magnetic field.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] These fields can generally be functions of position **r** and time t.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] where, as indicated in the figure, **Σ** is a surface bounded by the closed loop ∂**Σ** and d**l** is an infinitesimal vector element along that loop.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] The vector area element d**A** is perpendicular to the surface and oriented according to the right-hand rule: when the thumb points in the direction of the d**A**, the curled fingers indicate the direction of d**l** along the boundary.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] The left-hand side of the equation represents the circulation of the electric field around the loop ∂**Σ**.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] For static electric fields, the circulation is zero, since the field can be expressed as the gradient of a scalar potential.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] In contrast, a time-varying magnetic field produces a non-conservative electric field with nonzero circulation.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] When such field acts on a conducting loop, it drives a current around the loop.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] The four Maxwell's equations, together with the Lorentz force law, form a complete foundation for classical electromagnetism.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] From these, Faraday's law can be derived directly.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] By Gauss's law for magnetism (⁠ $\nabla \cdot \mathbf {B} =0$ ⁠), the second term under the area integral vanishes.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] However, the quantity inside the integral is not the full Lorentz force per unit charge, because the velocity $\mathbf {v} _{c}$ represents the motion of loop boundary, not the actual velocity of the charge carriers.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] To recover the physical electromotive force, we must distinguish between these velocities.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] Let us choose the integration path to coincide with the physical circuit.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] This decomposition assumes nonrelativistic (Galilean) addition of velocities.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] In circuits made of thin, one-dimensional wires, the drift velocity is aligned with the wire, and hence with the integration element ⁠ $\mathrm {d} \mathbf {l}$ ⁠.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] In that case, the cross product ${\textstyle \mathbf {v} _{d}\times \mathbf {B} }$ is perpendicular to ⁠ $\mathrm {d} \mathbf {l}$ ⁠, and the term proportional to the drift velocity vanishes.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] However, electrons typically drift at speeds of the order of 10−4 m/s, and the contribution is often negligible compared to other effects.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] A notable exception is the Hall effect, where magnetic flux term ${\textstyle \mathrm {d} \Phi _{B}/\mathrm {d} t}$ vanishes, and the observed Hall voltage arises entirely from the drift velocity term.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] It is tempting to generalize Faraday's law to state: *If*∂Σ*is any arbitrary closed loop in space whatsoever, then the total time derivative of magnetic flux through*Σ*equals the emf around*∂Σ*.* This statement, however, is not always true.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] As noted in the previous section, Faraday's law is not guaranteed to work unless the velocity of the abstract curve ∂Σ matches the actual velocity of the material conducting the electricity.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] If the conductor is not an infinitely thin wire, one may also have take into account the velocity of charges with respect to the material.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] The two examples illustrated below show that one often obtains incorrect results when Faraday's law is applied too broadly.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] One can analyze examples like these by taking care that the path ∂Σ moves with the same velocity as the material.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] The time derivative cannot in general be moved outside the integral since the position or shape of the loop may be a function of time.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] Historically, the two distinct mechanisms encompassed by the flux rule, motional emf and transformer emf, posed a conceptual challenge.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] James Clerk Maxwell already recognized that electromagnetic induction could arise through different physical processes, even though the induced emf obeyed a single mathematical expression.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] In his 1861 paper *On Physical Lines of Force*, he gave separate physical explanations for each case.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] In 1905, Albert Einstein highlighted this asymmetry in classical electrodynamics in his paper *On the Electrodynamics of Moving Bodies*.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] He pointed out that the physical outcome, such as the induced current, depends only on relative motion between the conductor and the magnet, yet classical theory provided different explanations depending on which object was considered to be in motion.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] This inconsistency suggested the absence of a preferred frame and helped motivate the development of special relativity.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] In modern terms, electric and magnetic fields are understood as components of a single electromagnetic field tensor.
[src:maxwell-equations/faraday-s-law-of-induction] Under a change of inertial frame, the two fields transform into one another.
[src:maxwell-equations/gauss-s-law] In electromagnetism, **Gauss's law**, also known as **Gauss's flux theorem** or sometimes **Gauss's theorem**, is one of Maxwell's equations.
[src:maxwell-equations/gauss-s-law] It is an application of the divergence theorem, and it relates the distribution of electric charge to the resulting electric field.
[src:maxwell-equations/gauss-s-law] In its integral form, it states that the flux of the electric field out of an arbitrary closed surface is proportional to the electric charge enclosed by the surface, irrespective of how that charge is distributed.
[src:maxwell-equations/gauss-s-law] Even though the law alone is insufficient to determine the electric field across a surface enclosing any charge distribution, this may be possible in cases where symmetry mandates uniformity of the field.
[src:maxwell-equations/gauss-s-law] Where no such symmetry exists, Gauss's law can be used in its differential form, which states that the divergence of the electric field is proportional to the local density of charge.
[src:maxwell-equations/gauss-s-law] The law was first formulated by Joseph-Louis Lagrange in 1773, followed by Carl Friedrich Gauss in 1835, both in the context of the attraction of ellipsoids.
[src:maxwell-equations/gauss-s-law] It is one of Maxwell's equations, which forms the basis of classical electrodynamics.
[src:maxwell-equations/gauss-s-law] Gauss's law can be used to derive Coulomb's law, and vice versa.
[src:maxwell-equations/gauss-s-law] Gauss's law has a close mathematical similarity with a number of laws in other areas of physics, such as Gauss's law for magnetism and Gauss's law for gravity.
[src:maxwell-equations/gauss-s-law] In fact, any inverse-square law can be formulated in a way similar to Gauss's law: for example, Gauss's law itself is essentially equivalent to Coulomb's law, and Gauss's law for gravity is essentially equivalent to Newton's law of gravity, both of which are inverse-square laws.
[src:maxwell-equations/gauss-s-law] The law can be expressed mathematically using vector calculus in integral form and differential form; both are equivalent since they are related by the divergence theorem, also called Gauss's theorem.
[src:maxwell-equations/gauss-s-law] Each of these forms in turn can also be expressed two ways: In terms of a relation between the electric field **E** and the total electric charge, or in terms of the electric displacement field **D** and the *free* electric charge.
[src:maxwell-equations/gauss-s-law] Gauss's law can be stated using either the electric field **E** or the electric displacement field **D**.
[src:maxwell-equations/gauss-s-law] This section shows some of the forms with **E**; the form with **D** is below, as are other forms with **E**.
[src:maxwell-equations/gauss-s-law] where Φ*E* is the electric flux through a closed surface S enclosing any volume V, Q is the total charge enclosed within V, and *ε*0 is the electric constant.
[src:maxwell-equations/gauss-s-law] where **E** is the electric field, d**A** is a vector representing an infinitesimal element of area of the surface, and · represents the dot product of two vectors.
[src:maxwell-equations/gauss-s-law] Since the flux is defined as an *integral* of the electric field, this expression of Gauss's law is called the *integral form*.
[src:maxwell-equations/gauss-s-law] In problems involving conductors set at known potentials, the potential away from them is obtained by solving Laplace's equation, either analytically or numerically.
[src:maxwell-equations/gauss-s-law] The electric field is then calculated as the potential's negative gradient.
[src:maxwell-equations/gauss-s-law] The reverse problem, when the electric charge distribution is known and the electric field must be computed, is much more difficult.
[src:maxwell-equations/gauss-s-law] The total flux through a given surface gives little information about the electric field, and can go in and out of the surface in arbitrarily complicated patterns.
[src:maxwell-equations/gauss-s-law] An exception is if there is some symmetry in the problem, which mandates that the electric field passes through the surface in a uniform way.
[src:maxwell-equations/gauss-s-law] Then, if the total flux is known, the field itself can be deduced at every point.
[src:maxwell-equations/gauss-s-law] Common examples of symmetries which lend themselves to Gauss's law include: cylindrical symmetry, planar symmetry, and spherical symmetry.
[src:maxwell-equations/gauss-s-law] See the article Gaussian surface for examples where these symmetries are exploited to compute electric fields.
[src:maxwell-equations/gauss-s-law] where ∇ · **E** is the divergence of the electric field, *ε*0 is the vacuum permittivity and ρ is the total volume charge density (charge per unit volume).
[src:maxwell-equations/gauss-s-law] The integral and differential forms are mathematically equivalent, by the divergence theorem.
[src:maxwell-equations/gauss-s-law] for any closed surface S containing charge Q.
[src:maxwell-equations/gauss-s-law] By the relation between charge and charge density, this equation is equivalent to: $\iiint _{V}\nabla \cdot \mathbf {E} \,\mathrm {d} V=\iiint _{V}{\frac {\rho }{\varepsilon _{0}}}\,\mathrm {d} V$ for any volume V.
[src:maxwell-equations/gauss-s-law] In order for this equation to be *simultaneously true* for *every* possible volume V, it is necessary (and sufficient) for the integrands to be equal everywhere.
[src:maxwell-equations/gauss-s-law] $\nabla \cdot \mathbf {E} ={\frac {\rho }{\varepsilon _{0}}}.$ Thus the integral and differential forms are equivalent.
[src:maxwell-equations/gauss-s-law] The electric charge that arises in the simplest textbook situations would be classified as "free charge"—for example, the charge which is transferred in static electricity, or the charge on a capacitor plate.
[src:maxwell-equations/gauss-s-law] In contrast, "bound charge" arises only in the context of dielectric (polarizable) materials.
[src:maxwell-equations/gauss-s-law] (All materials are polarizable to some extent.) When such materials are placed in an external electric field, the electrons remain bound to their respective atoms, but shift a microscopic distance in response to the field, so that they're more on one side of the atom than the other.
[src:maxwell-equations/gauss-s-law] All these microscopic displacements add up to give a macroscopic net charge distribution, and this constitutes the "bound charge".
[src:maxwell-equations/gauss-s-law] Although microscopically all charge is fundamentally the same, there are often practical reasons for wanting to treat bound charge differently from free charge.
[src:maxwell-equations/gauss-s-law] The result is that the more fundamental Gauss's law, in terms of **E** (above), is sometimes put into the equivalent form below, which is in terms of **D** and the free charge only.
[src:maxwell-equations/gauss-s-law] where Φ*D* is the **D**-field flux through a surface S which encloses a volume V, and *Q*free is the free charge contained in V.
[src:maxwell-equations/gauss-s-law] where ∇ · **D** is the divergence of the electric displacement field, and *ρ*free is the free electric charge density.
[src:maxwell-equations/gauss-s-law] Proof that the formulations of Gauss's law in terms of free charge are equivalent to the formulations involving total charge.
[src:maxwell-equations/gauss-s-law] This completes the proof: The first equation is true by definition, and therefore the second equation is true if and only if the third equation is true.
[src:maxwell-equations/gauss-s-law] So the second and third equations are equivalent, which is what we wanted to prove.
[src:maxwell-equations/gauss-s-law] where ε is the permittivity of the material.
[src:maxwell-equations/gauss-s-law] For the case of vacuum (aka free space), *ε* = *ε*0.
[src:maxwell-equations/gauss-s-law] Strictly speaking, Gauss's law cannot be derived from Coulomb's law alone, since Coulomb's law gives the electric field due to an individual, electrostatic point charge only.
[src:maxwell-equations/gauss-s-law] However, Gauss's law *can* be proven from Coulomb's law if it is assumed, in addition, that the electric field obeys the superposition principle.
[src:maxwell-equations/gauss-s-law] The superposition principle states that the resulting field is the vector sum of fields generated by each particle (or the integral, if the charges are distributed smoothly in space).
[src:maxwell-equations/gauss-s-law] Using the "sifting property" of the Dirac delta function, we arrive at $\nabla \cdot \mathbf {E} (\mathbf {r} )={\frac {\rho (\mathbf {r} )}{\varepsilon _{0}}},$ which is the differential form of Gauss's law, as desired.
[src:maxwell-equations/gauss-s-law] Since Coulomb's law only applies to stationary charges, there is no reason to expect Gauss's law to hold for moving charges based on this derivation alone.
[src:maxwell-equations/gauss-s-law] In fact, Gauss's law does hold for moving charges, and, in this respect, Gauss's law is more general than Coulomb's law.
[src:maxwell-equations/gauss-s-law] It is true for all $\mathbf {r} \neq \mathbf {r'}$ that $\nabla _{\mathbf {r} }\cdot \mathbf {e} (\mathbf {r,r'} )=0$ .
[src:maxwell-equations/gauss-s-law] Consider now a compact set $V\subseteq R^{3}$ having a piecewise smooth boundary $\partial V$ such that $\Omega \cap V=\emptyset$ .
[src:maxwell-equations/gauss-s-law] Therefore the flux through a closed surface generated by some charge density outside (the surface) is null.
[src:maxwell-equations/gauss-s-law] Now consider $\mathbf {r} _{0}\in \Omega$ , and $B_{R}(\mathbf {r} _{0})\subseteq \Omega$ as the sphere centered in $\mathbf {r} _{0}$ having R as radius (it exists because $\Omega$ is an open set).
[src:maxwell-equations/gauss-s-law] Let $\mathbf {E} _{B_{R}}$ and $\mathbf {E} _{C}$ be the electric field created inside and outside the sphere respectively.
[src:maxwell-equations/gauss-s-law] The last equality follows by observing that $(\Omega \setminus B_{R}(\mathbf {r} _{0}))\cap B_{R}(\mathbf {r} _{0})=\emptyset$ , and the argument above.
[src:maxwell-equations/gauss-s-law] Where the last equality follows by the mean value theorem for integrals.
[src:maxwell-equations/gauss-s-law] Strictly speaking, Coulomb's law cannot be derived from Gauss's law alone, since Gauss's law does not give any information regarding the curl of **E** (see Helmholtz decomposition and Faraday's law).
[src:maxwell-equations/gauss-s-law] However, Coulomb's law *can* be proven from Gauss's law if it is assumed, in addition, that the electric field from a point charge is spherically symmetric (this assumption, like Coulomb's law itself, is exactly true if the charge is stationary, and approximately true if the charge is in motion).
[src:maxwell-equations/gauss-s-law] By the assumption of spherical symmetry, the integrand is a constant which can be taken out of the integral.
[src:maxwell-equations/gauss-s-law] The result is $4\pi r^{2}{\hat {\mathbf {r} }}\cdot \mathbf {E} (\mathbf {r} )={\frac {Q}{\varepsilon _{0}}}$ where **r̂** is a unit vector pointing radially away from the charge.
[src:maxwell-equations/gauss-s-law] Again by spherical symmetry, **E** points in the radial direction, and so we get $\mathbf {E} (\mathbf {r} )={\frac {Q}{4\pi \varepsilon _{0}}}{\frac {\hat {\mathbf {r} }}{r^{2}}}$ which is essentially equivalent to Coulomb's law.
[src:maxwell-equations/gauss-s-law] Thus the inverse-square law dependence of the electric field in Coulomb's law follows from Gauss's law.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] The term "Maxwell's equations" is often also used for equivalent alternative formulations.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] Versions of Maxwell's equations based on the electric and magnetic scalar potentials are preferred for explicitly solving the equations as a boundary value problem, analytical mechanics, or for use in quantum mechanics.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] The covariant formulation (on spacetime rather than space and time separately) makes the compatibility of Maxwell's equations with special relativity manifest.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] Maxwell's equations in curved spacetime, commonly used in high-energy and gravitational physics, are compatible with general relativity.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] Maxwell's equations are named after the physicist and mathematician James Clerk Maxwell, who, in 1861 and 1862, published an early form of the equations that included the Lorentz force law.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] The publication of the equations marked the unification of a theory for previously separately described phenomena: magnetism, electricity, light, and associated radiation.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] The modern form of the equations in their most common formulation is credited to Oliver Heaviside.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] Since the mid-20th century, it has been understood that Maxwell's equations do not give an exact description of electromagnetic phenomena, but are instead a classical limit of the more precise theory of quantum electrodynamics.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] The two most commonly used variants of Maxwell's equations are the *microscopic* and *macroscopic* differential form in SI units.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] The coefficient of the proportion is the permittivity of free space.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] Gauss's law for magnetism states that electric charges have no magnetic analogues, called magnetic monopoles; no north or south magnetic poles exist in isolation.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] Instead, the magnetic field of a material is attributed to a dipole, and the net outflow of the magnetic field through a closed surface is zero.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] Magnetic dipoles may be represented as loops of current or inseparable pairs of equal and opposite "magnetic charges".
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] Precisely, the total magnetic flux through a Gaussian surface is zero, and the magnetic field is a solenoidal vector field.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] The Maxwell–Faraday version of Faraday's law of induction describes how a time-varying magnetic field corresponds to the negative curl of an electric field.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] In integral form, it states that the work per unit charge required to move a charge around a closed loop equals the rate of change of the magnetic flux through the enclosed surface.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] The electromagnetic induction is the operating principle behind many electric generators: for example, a rotating bar magnet creates a changing magnetic field and generates an electric field in a nearby wire.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] The original law of Ampère states that magnetic fields relate to electric current.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] Maxwell's addition states that magnetic fields also relate to changing electric fields, which Maxwell called displacement current.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] The integral form states that electric and displacement currents are associated with a proportional magnetic field along any enclosing curve.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] Maxwell's modification of Ampère's circuital law is important because the laws of Ampère and Gauss must otherwise be adjusted for static fields.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] As a consequence, it predicts that a rotating magnetic field occurs with a changing electric field.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] A further consequence is the existence of self-sustaining electromagnetic waves which travel through empty space.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] The speed calculated for electromagnetic waves, which could be predicted from experiments on charges and currents, matches the speed of light; indeed, light *is* one form of electromagnetic radiation (as are X-rays, radio waves, and others).
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] Maxwell understood the connection between electromagnetic waves and light in 1861, thereby unifying the theories of electromagnetism and optics.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] In the electric and magnetic field formulation there are four equations that determine the fields for given charge and current distribution.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] A separate law of nature, the Lorentz force law, describes how the electric and magnetic fields act on charged particles and currents.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] By convention, a version of this law in the original equations by Maxwell is no longer included.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] The vector calculus formalism below, the work of Oliver Heaviside, has become standard.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] It is rotationally invariant, and therefore mathematically more transparent than Maxwell's original 20 equations in *x*, *y* and *z* components.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] The relativistic formulations are more symmetric and Lorentz invariant.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] For the same equations expressed using tensor calculus or differential forms (see *§ Alternative formulations*).
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] The differential and integral formulations are mathematically equivalent; both are useful.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] The integral formulation relates fields within a region of space to fields on the boundary and can often be used to simplify and directly calculate fields from symmetric distributions of charges and currents.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] On the other hand, the differential equations are purely *local* and are a more natural starting point for calculating the fields in more complicated (less symmetric) situations, for example using finite element analysis.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] Symbols in **bold** represent vector quantities, and symbols in *italics* represent scalar quantities, unless otherwise indicated.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] The equations introduce the electric field, **E**, a vector field, and the magnetic field, **B**, a pseudovector field, each generally having a time and location dependence.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] The equations are a little easier to interpret with time-independent surfaces and volumes.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] Time-independent surfaces and volumes are "fixed" and do not change over a given time interval.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] The definitions of charge, electric field, and magnetic field can be altered to simplify theoretical calculation, by absorbing dimensioned factors of *ε*0 and *μ*0 into the units (and thus redefining these).
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] With a corresponding change in the values of the quantities for the Lorentz force law this yields the same physics, i.e. trajectories of charged particles, or work done by an electric motor.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] Such modified definitions are conventionally used with the Gaussian (CGS) units.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] The equations simplify slightly when a system of quantities is chosen in the speed of light, *c*, is used for nondimensionalization, so that, for example, seconds and lightseconds are interchangeable, and *c* = 1.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] Further changes are possible by absorbing factors of 4*π*.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] This process, called rationalization, affects whether Coulomb's law or Gauss's law includes such a factor (see *Heaviside–Lorentz units*, used mainly in particle physics).
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] The equivalence of the differential and integral formulations are a consequence of the Gauss divergence theorem and the Kelvin–Stokes theorem.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] This is the differential equations formulation of Gauss equation up to a trivial rearrangement.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] which is satisfied for all Ω if and only if $\nabla \cdot \mathbf {B} =0$ everywhere.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] The equivalence of Faraday's law in differential and integral form follows likewise.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] The line integrals and curls are analogous to quantities in classical fluid dynamics: the circulation of a fluid is the line integral of the fluid's flow velocity field around a closed loop, and the vorticity of the fluid is the curl of the velocity field.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] The invariance of charge can be derived as a corollary of Maxwell's equations.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] The left-hand side of the Ampère–Maxwell law has zero divergence by the div–curl identity.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] In particular, in an isolated system the total charge is conserved.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] The quantity $\mu _{0}\varepsilon _{0}$ has the dimension (T/L)2.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] Already during Maxwell's lifetime, it was found that the known values for $\varepsilon _{0}$ and $\mu _{0}$ give $c\approx 2.998\times 10^{8}~{\text{m/s}}$ , then already known to be the speed of light in free space.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] This led him to propose that light and radio waves were propagating electromagnetic waves, since amply confirmed.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] In the new SI system, only *c* keeps its defined value, and the electron charge gets a defined value.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] In materials with relative permittivity, *ε*r, and relative permeability, *μ*r, the phase velocity of light becomes $v_{\text{p}}={\frac {1}{\sqrt {\mu _{0}\mu _{\text{r}}\varepsilon _{0}\varepsilon _{\text{r}}}}},$ which is usually less than *c*.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] In addition, **E** and **B** are perpendicular to each other and to the direction of wave propagation, and are in phase with each other.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] A sinusoidal plane wave is one special solution of these equations.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] Maxwell's equations explain how these waves can physically propagate through space.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] The changing magnetic field creates a changing electric field through Faraday's law.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] In turn, that electric field creates a changing magnetic field through Maxwell's modification of Ampère's circuital law.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] This perpetual cycle allows these waves, now known as electromagnetic radiation, to move through space at velocity *c*.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] The above equations are the microscopic version of Maxwell's equations, expressing the electric and the magnetic fields in terms of the (possibly atomic-level) charges and currents present.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] This is sometimes called the "general" form, but the macroscopic version below is equally general, the difference being one of bookkeeping.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] The microscopic version is sometimes called "Maxwell's equations in vacuum": this refers to the fact that the material medium is not built into the structure of the equations, but appears only in the charge and current terms.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] The microscopic version was introduced by Lorentz, who tried to use it to derive the macroscopic properties of bulk matter from its microscopic constituents.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] "Maxwell's macroscopic equations", also known as **Maxwell's equations in matter**, are more similar to those that Maxwell introduced himself.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] In the macroscopic equations, the influence of bound charge *Q*b and bound current *I*b is incorporated into the displacement field **D** and the magnetizing field **H**, while the equations depend only on the free charges *Q*f and free currents *I*f.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] The cost of this splitting is that the additional fields **D** and **H** need to be determined through phenomenological constituent equations relating these fields to the electric field **E** and the magnetic field **B**, together with the bound charge and current.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] See below for a detailed description of the differences between the microscopic equations, dealing with *total* charge and current including material contributions, useful in air/vacuum; and the macroscopic equations, dealing with *free* charge and current, practical to use within materials.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] When an electric field is applied to a dielectric material its molecules respond by forming microscopic electric dipoles – their atomic nuclei move a tiny distance in the direction of the field, while their electrons move a tiny distance in the opposite direction.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] This produces a *macroscopic* *bound charge* in the material even though all of the charges involved are bound to individual molecules.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] For example, if every molecule responds the same, similar to that shown in the figure, these tiny movements of charge combine to produce a layer of positive bound charge on one side of the material and a layer of negative charge on the other side.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] The bound charge is most conveniently described in terms of the polarization **P** of the material, its dipole moment per unit volume.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] If **P** is uniform, a macroscopic separation of charge is produced only at the surfaces where **P** enters and leaves the material.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] For non-uniform **P**, a charge is also produced in the bulk.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] Somewhat similarly, in all materials the constituent atoms exhibit magnetic moments that are intrinsically linked to the angular momentum of the components of the atoms, most notably their electrons.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] The connection to angular momentum suggests the picture of an assembly of microscopic current loops.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] Outside the material, an assembly of such microscopic current loops is not different from a macroscopic current circulating around the material's surface, despite the fact that no individual charge is traveling a large distance.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] These *bound currents* can be described using the magnetization **M**.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] As such, *Maxwell's macroscopic equations* ignore many details on a fine scale that can be unimportant to understanding matters on a gross scale by calculating fields that are averaged over some suitable volume.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] In order to apply 'Maxwell's macroscopic equations', it is necessary to specify the relations between displacement field **D** and the electric field **E**, as well as the magnetizing field **H** and the magnetic field **B**.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] Equivalently, we have to specify the dependence of the polarization **P** (hence the bound charge) and the magnetization **M** (hence the bound current) on the applied electric and magnetic field.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] The equations specifying this response are called constitutive relations.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] For real-world materials, the constitutive relations are rarely simple, except approximately, and usually determined by experiment.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] See the main article on constitutive relations for a fuller description.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] For materials without polarization and magnetization, the constitutive relations are (by definition) $\mathbf {D} =\varepsilon _{0}\mathbf {E} ,\quad \mathbf {H} ={\frac {1}{\mu _{0}}}\mathbf {B} ,$ where *ε*0 is the permittivity of free space and *μ*0 the permeability of free space.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] Since there is no bound charge, the total and the free charge and current are equal.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] An alternative viewpoint on the microscopic equations is that they are the macroscopic equations *together* with the statement that vacuum behaves like a perfect linear "material" without additional polarization and magnetization.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] More generally, for linear materials the constitutive relations are $\mathbf {D} =\varepsilon \mathbf {E} ,\quad \mathbf {H} ={\frac {1}{\mu }}\mathbf {B} ,$ where *ε* is the permittivity and *μ* the permeability of the material.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] For the magnetizing field $\mathbf {H}$ , however, the linear approximation can break down in common materials like iron leading to phenomena like hysteresis.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] Even the linear case can have various complications, however.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] Even more generally, in the case of non-linear materials (see for example nonlinear optics), **D** and **P** are not necessarily proportional to **E**, similarly **H** or **M** is not necessarily proportional to **B**.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] In general **D** and **H** depend on both **E** and **B**, on location and time, and possibly other physical quantities.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] In applications one also has to describe how the free currents and charge density behave in terms of **E** and **B** possibly coupled to other physical quantities like pressure, and the mass, number density, and velocity of charge-carrying particles.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] Following are some of the several other mathematical formalisms of Maxwell's equations, with the columns separating the two homogeneous Maxwell equations from the two inhomogeneous ones.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] Each formulation has versions directly in terms of the electric and magnetic fields, and indirectly in terms of the electrical potential *φ* and the vector potential **A**.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] Potentials were introduced as a convenient way to solve the homogeneous equations, but it was thought that all observable physics was contained in the electric and magnetic fields (or relativistically, the Faraday tensor).
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] The potentials play a central role in quantum mechanics, however, and act quantum mechanically with observable consequences even when the electric and magnetic fields vanish (Aharonov–Bohm effect).
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] See the main article for details of each formulation.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] The direct spacetime formulations make manifest that the Maxwell equations are relativistically invariant, where space and time are treated on equal footing.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] Because of this symmetry, the electric and magnetic fields are treated on equal footing and are recognized as components of the Faraday tensor.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] This reduces the four Maxwell equations to two, which simplifies the equations, although we can no longer use the familiar vector formulation.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] Maxwell equations in formulation that do not treat space and time manifestly on the same footing have Lorentz invariance as a hidden symmetry.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] This was a major source of inspiration for the development of relativity theory.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] Indeed, even the formulation that treats space and time separately is not a non-relativistic approximation and describes the same physics by simply renaming variables.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] For this reason the relativistic invariant equations are usually called the Maxwell equations as well.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] Each table below describes one formalism.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] Other formalisms include the geometric algebra formulation and a matrix representation of Maxwell's equations.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] Historically, a quaternionic formulation was used.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] Maxwell's equations are partial differential equations that relate the electric and magnetic fields to each other and to the electric charges and currents.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] Often, the charges and currents are themselves dependent on the electric and magnetic fields via the Lorentz force equation and the constitutive relations.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] These all form a set of coupled partial differential equations which are often very difficult to solve: the solutions encompass all the diverse phenomena of classical electromagnetism.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] As for any differential equation, boundary conditions and initial conditions are necessary for a unique solution.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] For example, even with no charges and no currents anywhere in spacetime, there are the obvious solutions for which **E** and **B** are zero or constant, but there are also non-trivial solutions corresponding to electromagnetic waves.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] In some cases, Maxwell's equations are solved over the whole of space, and boundary conditions are given as asymptotic limits at infinity.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] Jefimenko's equations (or the closely related Liénard–Wiechert potentials) are the explicit solution to Maxwell's equations for the electric and magnetic fields created by any given distribution of charges and currents.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] It assumes specific initial conditions to obtain the so-called "retarded solution", where the only fields present are the ones created by the charges.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] However, Jefimenko's equations are unhelpful in situations when the charges and currents are themselves affected by the fields they create.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] Numerical methods for differential equations can be used to compute approximate solutions of Maxwell's equations when exact solutions are impossible.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] These include the finite element method and finite-difference time-domain method.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] For more details, see Computational electromagnetics.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] Maxwell's equations *seem* overdetermined, in that they involve six unknowns (the three components of **E** and **B**) but eight equations (one for each of the two Gauss's laws, three vector components each for Faraday's and Ampère's circuital laws).
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] This explanation was first introduced by Julius Adams Stratton in 1941.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] Although it is possible to simply ignore the two Gauss's laws in a numerical algorithm (apart from the initial conditions), the imperfect precision of the calculations can lead to ever-increasing violations of those laws.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] By introducing dummy variables characterizing these violations, the four equations become not overdetermined after all.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] The resulting formulation can lead to more accurate algorithms that take all four laws into account.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] Both identities $\nabla \cdot \nabla \times \mathbf {B} \equiv 0,\nabla \cdot \nabla \times \mathbf {E} \equiv 0$ , which reduce eight equations to six independent ones, are the true reason of overdetermination.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] Equivalently, the overdetermination can be viewed as implying conservation of electric and magnetic charge, as they are required in the derivation described above but implied by the two Gauss's laws.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] For linear algebraic equations, one can make 'nice' rules to rewrite the equations and unknowns.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] The equations can be linearly dependent.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] But in differential equations, and especially partial differential equations (PDEs), one needs appropriate boundary conditions, which depend in not so obvious ways on the equations.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] Even more, if one rewrites them in terms of vector and scalar potential, then the equations are underdetermined because of gauge fixing.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] Maxwell's equations and the Lorentz force law (along with the rest of classical electromagnetism) are extraordinarily successful at explaining and predicting a variety of phenomena.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] However, they do not account for quantum effects, and so their domain of applicability is limited.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] Maxwell's equations are thought of as the classical limit of quantum electrodynamics (QED).
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] Some observed electromagnetic phenomena cannot be explained with Maxwell's equations if the source of the electromagnetic fields are the classical distributions of charge and current.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] These include photon–photon scattering and many other phenomena related to photons or virtual photons, "nonclassical light" and quantum entanglement of electromagnetic fields (see *Quantum optics*).
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] E.g. quantum cryptography cannot be described by Maxwell theory, not even approximately.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] The approximate nature of Maxwell's equations becomes more and more apparent when going into the extremely strong field regime (see *Euler–Heisenberg Lagrangian*) or to extremely small distances.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] Finally, Maxwell's equations cannot explain any phenomenon involving individual photons interacting with quantum matter, such as the photoelectric effect, Planck's law, the Duane–Hunt law, and single-photon light detectors.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] However, many such phenomena may be explained using a halfway theory of quantum matter coupled to a classical electromagnetic field, either as external field or with the expected value of the charge current and density on the right hand side of Maxwell's equations.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] This is known as semiclassical theory or self-field QED and was initially discovered by de Broglie and Schrödinger and later fully developed by E.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] Popular variations on the Maxwell equations as a classical theory of electromagnetic fields are relatively scarce because the standard equations have stood the test of time remarkably well.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] Maxwell's equations posit that there is electric charge, but no magnetic charge (also called magnetic monopoles), in the universe.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] Indeed, magnetic charge has never been observed, despite extensive searches, and may not exist.
[src:maxwell-equations/maxwell-s-equations] If they did exist, both Gauss's law for magnetism and Faraday's law would need to be modified, and the resulting four equations would be fully symmetric under the interchange of electric and magnetic fields.
